<h3><a id="user-content-data-earlyterminationevent" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-earlyterminationevent"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>EarlyTerminationEvent</code></h3>
<p>A class to define the adjusted dates associated with
an early termination provision.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>EarlyTerminationEvent</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>
<th align="left">Type/Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>adjustedCashSettlementPaymentDate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Date</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The date on which the cash settlement amount is paid. This date should already be adjusted for any applicable business date convention.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>adjustedCashSettlementValuationDate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Date</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The date by which the cash settlement amount must be agreed. This date should already be adjusted for any applicable business day convention.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>adjustedEarlyTerminationDate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Date</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The early termination date that is applicable if an early termination provision is exercised. This date should already be adjusted for any applicable business day convention.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>adjustedExerciseDate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Date</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The date on which option exercise takes place. This date should already be adjusted for any applicable business day convention.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>adjustedExerciseFeePaymentDate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Date</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The date on which the exercise fee amount is paid. This date should already be adjusted for any applicable business day convention.</td>
</tr>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-event" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-event"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>Event</code></h3>
<p>A class to specify the lifecycle event. The
associated rosettaKey denotes the ability to
associate a hash value to the Event instantiation for
the purpose of model cross-referencing, in support of
functionality such as the event effect and the
lineage.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>Event</code></p>

<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>

</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>account</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>Account</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Optional account information that could be associated to the event.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>action</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>ActionEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Specifies whether the event is a new, a correction or a cancellation.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>effectiveDate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Date</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The date on which the event contractually takes effect, when different from the event date.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>eventDate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Date</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The date on which the event is taking place. This is the equivalent of the trade date in the case of an execution or a contract.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>eventEffect</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>EventEffect</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The set of effects associated with the lifecycle event, i.e. generated cashflows, contracts (from, say, novation events), listed products (from, say, a bond option exercise event)  values and more. Those are represented through a set of rosettaKey references. This attribute is optional in order to provide implementers with the ability not to make use of this feature.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>eventIdentifier</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>Identifier</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The identifier(s) that uniquely identify a lifecycle event. The unbounded cardinality is meant to provide the ability to associate identifiers that are issued by distinct parties. As an example, each of the parties to the event may choose to associate their own identifiers to the event.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>eventQualifier</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The CDM event qualifier, which corresponds to the outcome of the isEvent qualification logic which qualifies the lifecycle event as a function of its features (e.g. PartialTermination, ClearingSubmission, Novation, ...).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>eventWorkflow</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>EventWorkflow</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The event workflow information, i.e. the workflow status, the associated comment and the partyCustomisedWorkflow which purpose is to provide the ability to associate custom workflow information to the CDM.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>functionCall</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">This is placeholder concept for a function call into a calculation that will return an outcome. This concept needs to be further firmed out.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>id</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>intent</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>IntentEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The intent attribute is meant to be specified when the event qualification cannot be programmatically inferred from the event features. As a result it is only associated with those primitives that can give way to such ambiguity, the quantityChange being one of those. An example of such is a reduction in the trade notional, which could be interpreted as either a trade correction (unless a maximum period of time post-event is specified as part of the qualification), a partial termination or a portfolio rebalancing in the case of an equity swap. On the other hand, an event such as the exercise is not expected to have an associated intent as there should not be ambiguity.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>lineage</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Lineage</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The lineage attribute provides a linkage among lifecycle events through the rosettaKey hash value. One example is when a given lifecycle event is being corrected or cancelled. In such case, each subsequent event will have lineage into the prior version of that event. The second broad use case is when an event has a dependency upon either another event (e.g. the regular payment associated with a fix/float swap will have a lineage into the reset event, which will in turn have a lineage into the observation event for the floating rate and the contract) or a contract (e.g. the exercise of an option has a lineage into that option).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>messageInformation</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>MessageInformation</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>party</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>Party</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The specification of the event parties. This attribute is optional, as not applicable to certain events (e.g. most of the observations).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>primitive</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>PrimitiveEvent</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The elemental component(s) that specify the lifecycle events. Each of the primitive/elemental components listed as part of the PrimitiveEvent class has distinctive features that allow to specify the lifecycle event, either by itself or in combination with some other of such components.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>rosettaKey</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>timestamp</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>EventTimestamp</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The set of timestamp(s) associated with the event as a collection of [dateTime, qualifier].</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</li>
</ul>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-exerciseprocedure" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-exerciseprocedure"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>ExerciseProcedure</code></h3>
<p>A class describing how notice of exercise should be
given. This can be either manual or automatic.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>ExerciseProcedure</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>
<th align="left">Type/Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>automaticExercise</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>AutomaticExercise</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">If automatic is specified, then the notional amount of the underlying swap not previously exercised under the swaption will be automatically exercised at the expiration time on the expiration date if at such time the buyer is in-the-money, provided that the difference between the settlement rate and the fixed rate under the relevant underlying swap is not less than the specified threshold rate. The term in-the-money is assumed to have the meaning defining in the 2000 ISDA Definitions, Section 17.4 In-the-money.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>followUpConfirmation</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A flag to indicate whether follow-up confirmation of exercise (written or electronic) is required following telephonic notice by the buyer to the seller or seller's agent.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>limitedRightToConfirm</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Has the meaning defined as part of the 1997 ISDA Government Bond Option Definitions, section 4.5 Limited Right to Confirm Exercise. If present, (i) the Seller may request the Buyer to confirm its intent if not done on or before the expiration time on the Expiration date (ii) specific rules will apply in relation to the settlement mode.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>manualExercise</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>ManualExercise</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Specifies that the notice of exercise must be given by the buyer to the seller or seller's agent.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>splitTicket</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Typically applicable to the physical settlement of bond and convertible bond options. If present, means that the party required to deliver the bonds will divide those to be delivered as notifying party desires to facilitate delivery obligations.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</li>
</ul>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-floatingrate" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-floatingrate"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>FloatingRate</code></h3>
<p>A class defining a floating interest rate through the
specification of the floating rate index, the tenor,
the multiplier schedule, the spread, the
qualification of whether a specific rate treatment
and/or a cap or floor apply.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>FloatingRate</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>
<th align="left">Type/Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>capRateSchedule</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>StrikeSchedule</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The cap rate or cap rate schedule, if any, which applies to the floating rate. The cap rate (strike) is only required where the floating rate on a swap stream is capped at a certain level. A cap rate schedule is expressed as explicit cap rates and dates and the step dates may be subject to adjustment in accordance with any adjustments specified in calculationPeriodDatesAdjustments. The cap rate is assumed to be exclusive of any spread and is a per annum rate, expressed as a decimal. A cap rate of 5% would be represented as 0.05.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>floatingRateIndex</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>FieldWithMeta</code> <code>FloatingRateIndexEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The reference index that is used to specify the floating interest rate. The FpML standard maintains the list of such indices, which are positioned as enumeration values as part of the CDM.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>floatingRateMultiplierSchedule</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Schedule</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A rate multiplier or multiplier schedule to apply to the floating rate. A multiplier schedule is expressed as explicit multipliers and dates. In the case of a schedule, the step dates may be subject to adjustment in accordance with any adjustments specified in the calculationPeriodDatesAdjustments. The multiplier can be a positive or negative decimal. This element should only be included if the multiplier is not equal to 1 (one) for the term of the stream.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>floorRateSchedule</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>StrikeSchedule</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The floor rate or floor rate schedule, if any, which applies to the floating rate. The floor rate (strike) is only required where the floating rate on a swap stream is floored at a certain strike level. A floor rate schedule is expressed as explicit floor rates and dates and the step dates may be subject to adjustment in accordance with any adjustments specified in calculationPeriodDatesAdjustments. The floor rate is assumed to be exclusive of any spread and is a per annum rate, expressed as a decimal. A floor rate of 5% would be represented as 0.05.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>id</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>indexTenor</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Period</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The ISDA Designated Maturity, i.e. the floating rate tenor.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>rateTreatment</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>RateTreatmentEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The specification of any rate conversion which needs to be applied to the observed rate before being used in any calculations. The two common conversions are for securities quoted on a bank discount basis which will need to be converted to either a Money Market Yield or Bond Equivalent Yield. See the Annex to the 2000 ISDA Definitions, Section 7.3. Certain General Definitions Relating to Floating Rate Options, paragraphs (g) and (h) for definitions of these terms.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>spreadSchedule</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>SpreadSchedule</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The ISDA Spread or a Spread schedule expressed as explicit spreads and dates. In the case of a schedule, the step dates may be subject to adjustment in accordance with any adjustments specified in calculationPeriodDatesAdjustments. The spread is a per annum rate, expressed as a decimal. For purposes of determining a calculation period amount, if positive the spread will be added to the floating rate and if negative the spread will be subtracted from the floating rate. A positive 10 basis point (0.1%) spread would be represented as 0.001.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</li>
</ul>
<h3><a id="user-content-data-floatingratedefinition" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-floatingratedefinition"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>FloatingRateDefinition</code></h3>

<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A rate multiplier or multiplier schedule to apply to the floating rate. A multiplier schedule is expressed as explicit multipliers and dates. In the case of a schedule, the step dates may be subject to adjustment in accordance with any adjustments specified in the calculationPeriodDatesAdjustments. The multiplier can be a positive or negative decimal. This element should only be included if the multiplier is not equal to 1 (one) for the term of the stream.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>floorRateSchedule</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>StrikeSchedule</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The floor rate or floor rate schedule, if any, which applies to the floating rate. The floor rate (strike) is only required where the floating rate on a swap stream is floored at a certain strike level. A floor rate schedule is expressed as explicit floor rates and dates and the step dates may be subject to adjustment in accordance with any adjustments specified in calculationPeriodDatesAdjustments. The floor rate is assumed to be exclusive of any spread and is a per annum rate, expressed as a decimal. A floor rate of 5% would be represented as 0.05.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>id</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>indexTenor</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Period</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The ISDA Designated Maturity, i.e. the floating rate tenor.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>initialRate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Decimal</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The initial floating rate reset agreed between the principal parties involved in the trade. This is assumed to be the first required reset rate for the first regular calculation period. It should only be included when the rate is not equal to the rate published on the source implied by the floating rate index. An initial rate of 5% would be represented as 0.05.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>negativeInterestRateTreatment</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>NegativeInterestRateTreatmentEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The specification of any provisions for calculating payment obligations when a floating rate is negative (either due to a quoted negative floating rate or by operation of a spread that is subtracted from the floating rate).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>rateTreatment</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>RateTreatmentEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The specification of any rate conversion which needs to be applied to the observed rate before being used in any calculations. The two common conversions are for securities quoted on a bank discount basis which will need to be converted to either a Money Market Yield or Bond Equivalent Yield. See the Annex to the 2000 ISDA Definitions, Section 7.3. Certain General Definitions Relating to Floating Rate Options, paragraphs (g) and (h) for definitions of these terms.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>spreadSchedule</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>SpreadSchedule</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The ISDA Spread or a Spread schedule expressed as explicit spreads and dates. In the case of a schedule, the step dates may be subject to adjustment in accordance with any adjustments specified in calculationPeriodDatesAdjustments. The spread is a per annum rate, expressed as a decimal. For purposes of determining a calculation period amount, if positive the spread will be added to the floating rate and if negative the spread will be subtracted from the floating rate. A positive 10 basis point (0.1%) spread would be represented as 0.001.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</li>
</ul>

<p>A class that specifies the source for and timing of a

agreement of non-deliverable forward trades as well

<li>

<ul>

<th align="left">Field</th>

<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>BusinessCenters</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>businessCentersReference</code></td>

</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A reference to a set of financial business centers defined elsewhere in the document. This set of business centers is used to determine whether a particular day is a business day or not.</td>

</tr>

</tr>

Implemented for Brazilian-CDI swaps where it will refer to the termination date of the appropriate leg.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>dateRelativeToPaymentDates</code></td>

</tr>

</tr>
<tr>

</tr>

The financial business centers to use for determination of business days are implied by the context in which this element is used. This element must only be included when the offset is specified as a number of days. If the offset is zero days then the dayType element should not be included.</td>

<p>A class to describe a notional schedule where each

notional amount schedule in a different currency by

</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A pointer style reference to the associated constant notional schedule defined elsewhere in the document which contains the currency amounts which will be converted into the varying notional currency amounts using the spot currency exchange rate.</td>

</tr>
<tr>

<tr>

</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The initial currency amount for the varying notional. This may be omitted for a forward starting swap if the FX-linked notional value is not known at deal inception.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>varyingNotionalCurrency</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>FieldWithMeta</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The currency of the varying notional amount, i.e. the notional amount being determined periodically based on observation of a spot currency exchange rate. The list of valid currencies is not presently positioned as an enumeration as part of the CDM because that scope is limited to the values specified by ISDA and FpML. As a result, implementers have to make reference to the relevant standard, such as the ISO 4217 standard for currency codes.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>varyingNotionalFixingDates</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>RelativeDateOffset</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The dates on which spot currency exchange rates are observed for purposes of determining the varying notional currency amount that will apply to a calculation period.</td>

<tr>

<td align="left">The dates on which interim exchanges of notional are paid. Interim exchanges will arise as a result of changes in the spot currency exchange amount or changes in the constant notional schedule (e.g. amortisation).</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

</ul>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-inflationratespecification" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-inflationratespecification"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>InflationRateSpecification</code></h3>
<p>A class to specify the inflation rate.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>InflationRateSpecification</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>
<th align="left">Type/Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>averagingMethod</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>AveragingMethodEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">If averaging is applicable, this component specifies whether a weighted or unweighted average method of calculation is to be used. The component must only be included when averaging applies.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>capRateSchedule</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>StrikeSchedule</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The cap rate or cap rate schedule, if any, which applies to the floating rate. The cap rate (strike) is only required where the floating rate on a swap stream is capped at a certain level. A cap rate schedule is expressed as explicit cap rates and dates and the step dates may be subject to adjustment in accordance with any adjustments specified in calculationPeriodDatesAdjustments. The cap rate is assumed to be exclusive of any spread and is a per annum rate, expressed as a decimal. A cap rate of 5% would be represented as 0.05.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>fallbackBondApplicable</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The applicability of a fallback bond as defined in the 2006 ISDA Inflation Derivatives Definitions, sections 1.3 and 1.8.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>finalRateRounding</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Rounding</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The rounding convention to apply to the final rate used in determination of a calculation period amount.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>floatingRateIndex</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>FieldWithMeta</code> <code>FloatingRateIndexEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The reference index that is used to specify the floating interest rate. The FpML standard maintains the list of such indices, which are positioned as enumeration values as part of the CDM.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>floatingRateMultiplierSchedule</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Schedule</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A rate multiplier or multiplier schedule to apply to the floating rate. A multiplier schedule is expressed as explicit multipliers and dates. In the case of a schedule, the step dates may be subject to adjustment in accordance with any adjustments specified in the calculationPeriodDatesAdjustments. The multiplier can be a positive or negative decimal. This element should only be included if the multiplier is not equal to 1 (one) for the term of the stream.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>floorRateSchedule</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>StrikeSchedule</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The floor rate or floor rate schedule, if any, which applies to the floating rate. The floor rate (strike) is only required where the floating rate on a swap stream is floored at a certain strike level. A floor rate schedule is expressed as explicit floor rates and dates and the step dates may be subject to adjustment in accordance with any adjustments specified in calculationPeriodDatesAdjustments. The floor rate is assumed to be exclusive of any spread and is a per annum rate, expressed as a decimal. A floor rate of 5% would be represented as 0.05.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>id</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>indexSource</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>FieldWithMeta</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The reference source such as Reuters or Bloomberg. FpML specifies indexSource to be of type rateSourcePageScheme, but without specifying actual values.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>indexTenor</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Period</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The ISDA Designated Maturity, i.e. the floating rate tenor.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>inflationLag</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Offset</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An off-setting period from the payment date which determines the reference period for which the inflation index is observed.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>initialIndexLevel</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Decimal</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Initial known index level for the first calculation period.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>initialRate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Decimal</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The initial floating rate reset agreed between the principal parties involved in the trade. This is assumed to be the first required reset rate for the first regular calculation period. It should only be included when the rate is not equal to the rate published on the source implied by the floating rate index. An initial rate of 5% would be represented as 0.05.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>interpolationMethod</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>FieldWithMeta</code> <code>InterpolationMethodEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The method used when calculating the Inflation Index Level from multiple points. The most common is Linear.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>mainPublication</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>FieldWithMeta</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The current main publication source such as relevant web site or a government body. FpML specifies mainPublication to be of type mainPublicationSource, but without specifying actual values.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>negativeInterestRateTreatment</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>NegativeInterestRateTreatmentEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The specification of any provisions for calculating payment obligations when a floating rate is negative (either due to a quoted negative floating rate or by operation of a spread that is subtracted from the floating rate).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>rateTreatment</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>RateTreatmentEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The specification of any rate conversion which needs to be applied to the observed rate before being used in any calculations. The two common conversions are for securities quoted on a bank discount basis which will need to be converted to either a Money Market Yield or Bond Equivalent Yield. See the Annex to the 2000 ISDA Definitions, Section 7.3. Certain General Definitions Relating to Floating Rate Options, paragraphs (g) and (h) for definitions of these terms.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>spreadSchedule</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>SpreadSchedule</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The ISDA Spread or a Spread schedule expressed as explicit spreads and dates. In the case of a schedule, the step dates may be subject to adjustment in accordance with any adjustments specified in calculationPeriodDatesAdjustments. The spread is a per annum rate, expressed as a decimal. For purposes of determining a calculation period amount, if positive the spread will be added to the floating rate and if negative the spread will be subtracted from the floating rate. A positive 10 basis point (0.1%) spread would be represented as 0.001.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</li>
</ul>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-interestratepayout" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-interestratepayout"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>InterestRatePayout</code></h3>
<p>A class to specify all of the terms necessary to
define and calculate a cash flow based on a fixed, a
floating or an inflation index rate. The interest
rate payout can be applied to interest rate swaps and
FRA (which both have two associated interest rate
payouts), credit default swaps (to represent the fee
leg when subject to periodic payments) and equity
swaps (to represent the funding leg). The associated
rosettaKey denotes the ability to associate a hash
value to the InterestRatePayout instantiations for
the purpose of model cross-referencing, in support of
functionality such as the event effect and the
lineage.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>InterestRatePayout</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>
<th align="left">Type/Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>bondReference</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>BondReference</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Reference to a bond underlier to represent an asset swap or Condition Precedent Bond.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>calculationPeriodDates</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>CalculationPeriodDates</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The parameters used to generate the calculation period dates schedule, including the specification of any initial or final stub calculation periods.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>cashflowRepresentation</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>CashflowRepresentation</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The cashflow representation of the swap stream.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>compoundingMethod</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>CompoundingMethodEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">If one or more calculation period contributes to a single payment amount this element specifies whether compounding is applicable and, if so, what compounding method is to be used. This element must only be included when more than one calculation period contributes to a single payment amount.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>crossCurrencyTerms</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>CrossCurrencyTerms</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The specification of the principle exchange and settlement provision terms.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>dayCountFraction</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>(</code> <code>FieldWithMeta</code> <code>DayCountFractionEnum</code> <code>)</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The day count fraction. The cardinality has been relaxed when compared with the FpML interest rate swap for the purpose of accommodating standardized credit default swaps which DCF is not explicitly stated as part of the economic terms. The data rule InterestRatePayout_dayCountFraction requires that the DCF be stated for interest rate products.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>discountingMethod</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>DiscountingMethod</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The parameters specifying any discounting conventions that may apply. This element must only be included if discounting applies.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>fixedAmount</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Fixed Amount Calculation</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>floatingAmount</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Floating Amount Calculation</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>id</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>payerReceiver</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>PayerReceiver</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The payer/seller paradigm applies to swap products, whether interest rate swaps or the fee leg of credit default swaps.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>paymentDate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>AdjustableDate</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The payment date, where only one date is specified, as for the FRA product.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>paymentDates</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>PaymentDates</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The payment date schedule, as defined by the parameters that are needed to specify it, either in a parametric way or by reference to another schedule of dates (e.g. the reset dates).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>paymentDelay</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Applicable to CDS on MBS to specify whether payment delays are applicable to the fixed Amount. RMBS typically have a payment delay of 5 days between the coupon date of the reference obligation and the payment date of the synthetic swap. CMBS do not, on the other hand, with both payment dates being on the 25th of each month.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>quantity</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>ContractualQuantity</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The specification of the notional amount that is associated with a contractual product and that is the base for the payout calculation, through the ContractualQuantity class which provides a generic approach that is applicable across all asset classes. The quantity attribute applies to products relating to securities or tangible assets (such as equities or commodities), while the notional amount applies to products pertaining to interest rate, FX or credit products.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>rateSpecification</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>RateSpecification</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The specification of the rate value(s) applicable to the contract using either a floating rate calculation, a single fixed rate, a fixed rate schedule, or an inflation rate calculation.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>resetDates</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>ResetDates</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The reset dates schedule, i.e. the dates on which the new observed index value is applied for each period and the interest rate hence begins to accrue.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>rosettaKey</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>stubPeriod</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>StubPeriod</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The stub calculation period amount parameters. This element must only be included if there is an initial or final stub calculation period. Even then, it must only be included if either the stub references a different floating rate tenor to the regular calculation periods, or if the stub is calculated as a linear interpolation of two different floating rate tenors, or if a specific stub rate or stub amount has been negotiated.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</li>
</ul>
<h3><a id="user-content-data-interestshortfall" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-interestshortfall"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>InterestShortFall</code></h3>

<table>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-lineage" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-lineage"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>Lineage</code></h3>
<p>A class to provide lineage information across
lifecycle events through a pointer or set of pointers
into the event(s), contract(s) and, possibly, payout
components that the event is dependent on or relates
to. As an example, if an inception event is
corrected, the correction event will have a lineage
into the initial event, which takes the form of a
rosettaKey into that initial inception event. Two
referencing mechanisms are provided as part of the
CDM: either the rosettaKey, which corresponds to the
hash value of the CDM class which is referred to, or
a reference qualifier which is meant to provide
support for the ingestion of xml documents with
id/href mechanisms. The CDM recommends the use of the
rosettaKey and provides a default implementation
which is accessible in the generated code through
org.isda.cdm.rosettakey.RosettaKeyValueHashFunction.
If implementers want to use an alternative hashing
mechanism, the API in which they need to plug it is
com.rosetta.model.lib.HashFunction.</p>

<li>

<p>A class to specify loan with a participation
agreement whereby the buyer is capable of creating,
or procuring the creation of, a contractual right in
favour of the seller that provides the seller with
recourse to the participation seller for a specified
share in any payments due under the relevant loan
which are received by the participation seller. ISDA
2003 Term: Direct Loan Participation.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>LoanParticipation</code></p>

<thead>

<th align="left">Field</th>

</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>

</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>partialCashSettlement</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Specifies whether either 'Partial Cash Settlement of Assignable Loans', 'Partial Cash Settlement of Consent Required Loans' or 'Partial Cash Settlement of Participations' is applicable. If this element is specified and Assignable Loan is a Deliverable Obligation Characteristic, any Assignable Loan that is deliverable, but where a non-receipt of Consent by the Physical Settlement Date has occurred, the Loan can be cash settled rather than physically delivered. If this element is specified and Consent Required Loan is a Deliverable Obligation Characteristic, any Consent Required Loan that is deliverable, but where a non-receipt of Consent by the Physical Settlement Date has occurred, the Loan can be cash settled rather than physically delivered. If this element is specified and Direct Loan Participation is a Deliverable Obligation Characteristic, any Participation that is deliverable, but where this participation has not been effected (has not come into effect) by the Physical Settlement Date, the participation can be cash settled rather than physically delivered.</td>
</tr>
<tr>

<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>

<td align="left">If Direct Loan Participation is specified as a deliverable obligation characteristic, this specifies any requirements for the Qualifying Participation Seller. The requirements may be listed free-form. ISDA 2003 Term: Qualifying Participation Seller.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-multipleexercise" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-multipleexercise"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>MultipleExercise</code></h3>
<p>A class defining multiple exercises. As defined in
the 2000 ISDA Definitions, Section 12.4. Multiple
Exercise, the buyer of the option has the right to
exercise all or less than all the unexercised
notional amount of the underlying swap on one or more
days in the exercise period, but on any such day may
not exercise less than the minimum notional amount or
more than the maximum notional amount, and if an
integral multiple amount is specified, the notional
exercised must be equal to or, be an integral
multiple of, the integral multiple amount. In FpML,
MultipleExercise is built upon the
PartialExercise.model.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>MultipleExercise</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>
<th align="left">Type/Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>

<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Decimal</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A notional amount which restricts the amount of notional that can be exercised when partial exercise or multiple exercise is applicable. The integral multiple amount defines a lower limit of notional that can be exercised and also defines a unit multiple of notional that can be exercised, i.e. only integer multiples of this amount can be exercised.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>maximumNotionalAmount</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Decimal</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The maximum notional amount that can be exercised on a given exercise date.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>maximumNumberOfOptions</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Decimal</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The maximum number of options that can be exercised on a given exercise date. If the number is not specified, it means that the maximum number of options corresponds to the remaining unexercised options.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>minimumNotionalAmount</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Decimal</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The minimum notional amount that can be exercised on a given exercise date. See multipleExercise.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>minimumNumberOfOptions</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Int</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The minimum number of options that can be exercised on a given exercise date.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>notionaReference</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>ReferenceWithMeta</code> <code>Money</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>

<p>A class to specify a mutual fund as having a product
identifier. As a difference versus the FpML standard,
the CDM structure of this class only includes the
productIdentifier class, which consists of an
identifier, productTaxonomy, and source of the

the potential for conflicting information between the
information associated with the contractual product

<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The non-negative initial rate or amount, as the case may be. An initial rate of 5% would be represented as 0.05.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>step</code></td>

</tr>
<tr>

<td align="left">The schedule of step date and non-negative value pairs. On each step date the associated step value becomes effective. A list of steps may be ordered in the document by ascending step date. An FpML document containing an unordered list of steps is still regarded as a conformant document.</td>

</ul>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-notdomesticcurrency" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-notdomesticcurrency"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>NotDomesticCurrency</code></h3>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-notificationtime" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-notificationtime"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>NotificationTime</code></h3>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-notionalschedule" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-notionalschedule"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>NotionalSchedule</code></h3>
<p>A class specifying the notional amount or notional
amount schedule associated with a contractual
product. The notional schedule will be captured
explicitly, specifying the dates that the notional
changes and the outstanding notional amount that
applies from that date. A parametric representation
of the rules defining the notional step schedule can
optionally be included.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>NotionalSchedule</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>
<th align="left">Type/Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>id</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>notionalStepParameters</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>NotionalStepRule</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A parametric representation of the notional step schedule, to be used when the notional schedule is not just specified as a set of dates and notional amount. Those parameters include the step frequency, the first and last notional step dates, the step rate, ...</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>notionalStepSchedule</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>NonNegativeAmountSchedule</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The notional amount when expressed as a varying notional alongside a date schedule. The step dates may be subject to adjustments in accordance with any adjustments specified in calculationPeriodDatesAdjustments.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</li>
</ul>
<h3><a id="user-content-data-notionalsteprule" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-notionalsteprule"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>NotionalStepRule</code></h3>
<p>A class defining a parametric representation for the
notional step schedule, i.e. parameters used to
generate the notional amount on each step date. This
parametric representation is intended to cover the
more common amortizing/accreting variations of swaps.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>NotionalStepRule</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>
<th align="left">Type/Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>calculationPeriodDatesReference</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>ReferenceWithMeta</code> <code>CalculationPeriodDates</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A pointer style reference to the associated calculation period dates component defined elsewhere in the document.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>firstNotionalStepDate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Date</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Effective date of the first change in notional (i.e. a calculation period start date).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>lastNotionalStepDate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Date</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Effective date of the last change in notional (i.e. a calculation period start date).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>notionalStepAmount</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Decimal</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The explicit amount that the notional changes on each step date. This can be a positive or negative amount.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>notionalStepRate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Decimal</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The percentage amount by which the notional changes on each step date. The percentage is either a percentage applied to the initial notional amount or the previous outstanding notional, depending of the value of the attribute stepRelativeTo. The percentage can be either positive or negative. A percentage of 5% would be represented as 0.05.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>stepFrequency</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Frequency</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The frequency at which the notional step changes occur. This frequency must be an integer multiple of the stream calculation period frequency.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>stepRelativeTo</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>StepRelativeToEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Specifies whether the notionalStepRate should be applied to the initial notional or the previous notional in order to calculate the notional step change amount.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</li>
</ul>
<h3><a id="user-content-data-obligations" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-obligations"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>Obligations</code></h3>
<p>A class to specify the underlying obligations of the
reference entity on which protection is purchased or
sold through the Credit Default Swap.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>Obligations</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>
<th align="left">Type/Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>cashSettlementOnly</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An obligation and deliverable obligation characteristic. Defined in the ISDA published Standard Terms Supplement for use with CDS Transactions on Leveraged Loans. ISDA 2003 Term: Cash Settlement Only.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>category</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>ObligationCategoryEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Used in both obligations and deliverable obligations to represent a class or type of securities which apply. ISDA 2003 Term: Obligation Category/Deliverable Obligation Category.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>continuity</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An obligation and deliverable obligation characteristic. Defined in the ISDA published Standard Terms Supplement for use with CDS Transactions on Leveraged Loans. ISDA 2003 Term: Continuity.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>deliveryOfCommitments</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An obligation and deliverable obligation characteristic. Defined in the ISDA published Standard Terms Supplement for use with CDS Transactions on Leveraged Loans. ISDA 2003 Term: Delivery of Commitments.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>designatedPriority</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>(</code> <code>FieldWithMeta</code> <code>Text</code> <code>)</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Applies to Loan CDS, to indicate what lien level is appropriate for a deliverable obligation. Applies to European Loan CDS, to indicate the Ranking of the obligation. Example: a 2nd lien Loan CDS would imply that the deliverable obligations are 1st or 2nd lien loans.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>excluded</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A free format string to specify any excluded obligations or deliverable obligations, as the case may be, of the reference entity or excluded types of obligations or deliverable obligations. ISDA 2003 Term: Excluded Obligations/Excluded Deliverable Obligations.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>fullFaithAndCreditObLiability</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An obligation and deliverable obligation characteristic. Defined in the ISDA published additional provisions for U.S. Municipal as Reference Entity. ISDA 2003 Term: Full Faith and Credit Obligation Liability.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>generalFundObligationLiability</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An obligation and deliverable obligation characteristic. Defined in the ISDA published additional provisions for U.S. Municipal as Reference Entity. ISDA 2003 Term: General Fund Obligation Liability.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>listed</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An obligation and deliverable obligation characteristic. Indicates whether or not the obligation is quoted, listed or ordinarily purchased and sold on an exchange. ISDA 2003 Term: Listed.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>notContingent</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">OTE: Only allowed as an obligation characteristic under ISDA Credit 1999. In essence Not Contingent means the repayment of principal cannot be dependent on a formula/index, i.e. to prevent the risk of being delivered an instrument that may never pay any element of principal, and to ensure that the obligation is interest bearing (on a regular schedule). ISDA 2003 Term: Not Contingent.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>notDomesticCurrency</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>NotDomesticCurrency</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An obligation and deliverable obligation characteristic. Any obligation that is payable in any currency other than the domestic currency. Domestic currency is either the currency so specified or, if no currency is specified, the currency of (a) the reference entity, if the reference entity is a sovereign, or (b) the jurisdiction in which the relevant reference entity is organised, if the reference entity is not a sovereign. ISDA 2003 Term: Not Domestic Currency.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>notDomesticIssuance</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An obligation and deliverable obligation characteristic. Any obligation other than an obligation that was intended to be offered for sale primarily in the domestic market of the relevant Reference Entity. This specifies that the obligation must be an internationally recognised bond. ISDA 2003 Term: Not Domestic Issuance.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>notDomesticLaw</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An obligation and deliverable obligation characteristic. If the reference entity is a Sovereign, this means any obligation that is not subject to the laws of the reference entity. If the reference entity is not a sovereign, this means any obligation that is not subject to the laws of the jurisdiction of the reference entity. ISDA 2003 Term: Not Domestic Law.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>notSovereignLender</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An obligation and deliverable obligation characteristic. Any obligation that is not primarily (majority) owed to a Sovereign or Supranational Organisation. ISDA 2003 Term: Not Sovereign Lender.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>notSubordinated</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An obligation and deliverable obligation characteristic. An obligation that ranks at least equal with the most senior Reference Obligation in priority of payment or, if no Reference Obligation is specified in the related Confirmation, the obligations of the Reference Entity that are senior. ISDA 2003 Term: Not Subordinated.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>othReferenceEntityObligations</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">This element is used to specify any other obligations of a reference entity in both obligations and deliverable obligations. The obligations can be specified free-form. ISDA 2003 Term: Other Obligations of a Reference Entity.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>revenueObligationLiability</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An obligation and deliverable obligation characteristic. Defined in the ISDA published additional provisions for U.S. Municipal as Reference Entity. ISDA 2003 Term: Revenue Obligation Liability.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>specifiedCurrency</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>SpecifiedCurrency</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An obligation and deliverable obligation characteristic. The currency or currencies in which an obligation or deliverable obligation must be payable. ISDA 2003 Term: Specified Currency.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<ul>
<li>

<tr>

If a day type of business days is specified then non-business days are ignored when calculating the offset. The financial business centers to use for determination of business days are implied by the context in which this element is used. This element must only be included when the offset is specified as a number of days. If the offset is zero days then the dayType element should not be included.</td>

<td align="left"><code>PeriodEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>

</tr>
<tr>

<td align="left"><code>Int</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>

</tr>
</tbody>

</tr>
<tr>

<td align="left">Specifies whether either 'Partial Cash Settlement of Assignable Loans', 'Partial Cash Settlement of Consent Required Loans' or 'Partial Cash Settlement of Participations' is applicable. If this element is specified and Assignable Loan is a Deliverable Obligation Characteristic, any Assignable Loan that is deliverable, but where a non-receipt of Consent by the Physical Settlement Date has occurred, the Loan can be cash settled rather than physically delivered. If this element is specified and Consent Required Loan is a Deliverable Obligation Characteristic, any Consent Required Loan that is deliverable, but where a non-receipt of Consent by the Physical Settlement Date has occurred, the Loan can be cash settled rather than physically delivered. If this element is specified and Direct Loan Participation is a Deliverable Obligation Characteristic, any Participation that is deliverable, but where this participation has not been effected (has not come into effect) by the Physical Settlement Date, the participation can be cash settled rather than physically delivered.</td>

<p>A class defining partial exercise. As defined in the
2000 ISDA Definitions, Section 12.3 Partial Exercise,
the buyer of the option may exercise all or less than
all the notional amount of the underlying swap but
may not be less than the minimum notional amount (if
specified) and must be an integral multiple of the
integral multiple amount if specified.</p>

<td align="left">A notional amount which restricts the amount of notional that can be exercised when partial exercise or multiple exercise is applicable. </tr>
<tr>

</tr>
<tr>

<tr>

dates or valuation dates). The CDM representation

providing the ability to specify the payment dates as
a function of some other dates specified in the
instance document.</p>

</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The anchor date when the payment dates are specified by reference to a set of dates specified somewhere else in the instance document/transaction, e.g. the valuation dates as typically the case for equity swaps.  When this attribute is specified, the paymentDaysOffset and the paymentDatesAdjustments also need to specified.</td>
</tr>
<tr>

<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The first unadjusted payment date. This day may be subject to adjustment in accordance with any business day convention specified in paymentDatesAdjustments. This element must only be included if there is an initial stub. This date will normally correspond to an unadjusted calculation period start or end date. This is true even if early or delayed payment is specified to be applicable since the actual first payment date will be the specified number of days before or after the applicable adjusted calculation period start or end date with the resulting payment date then being adjusted in accordance with any business day convention specified in paymentDatesAdjustments.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>id</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>lastPaymentDate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>LastRegularPaymentDate</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The last payment date. In the case of interest rate swaps, FpML specifies that this date must only be included if there is a final stub, with all calculation periods after this date contributing to the final payment.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>payRelativeTo</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>PayRelativeToEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Specifies whether the payments occur relative to each adjusted calculation period start date or end date, each reset date, valuation date or the last pricing date. Calculation period start date means relative to the start of the first calculation period contributing to a given payment. Similarly, calculation period end date means the end of the last calculation period contributing to a given payment. The valuation date is applicable for Brazilian-CDI and equity swaps.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>paymentDatesAdjustments</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>BusinessDayAdjustments</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The definition of the business day convention and financial business centers used for adjusting the payment date if it would otherwise fall on a day that is not a business day in the specified business center.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>paymentDaysOffset</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Offset</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">If early payment or delayed payment is required, specifies the number of days offset that the payment occurs relative to what would otherwise be the unadjusted payment date. The offset can be specified in terms of either calendar or business days. Even in the case of a calendar days offset, the resulting payment date, adjusted for the specified calendar days offset, will still be adjusted in accordance with the specified payment dates adjustments. This element should only be included if early or delayed payment is applicable, i.e. if the periodMultiplier element value is not equal to zero. An early payment would be indicated by a negative periodMultiplier element value and a delayed payment (or payment lag) would be indicated by a positive periodMultiplier element value.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>paymentFrequency</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Frequency</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The frequency at which regular payment dates occur. If the payment frequency is equal to the frequency defined in the calculation period dates component then one calculation period contributes to each payment amount. If the payment frequency is less frequent than the frequency defined in the calculation period dates component then more than one calculation period will contribute to the payment amount. A payment frequency more frequent than the calculation period frequency or one that is not a multiple of the calculation period frequency is invalid. If the payment frequency is of value T (term), the period is defined by the effectiveDate and the terminationDate.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</li>
</ul>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-payout" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-payout"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>Payout</code></h3>
<p>A class to represent the set of future cashflow
methodologies in the form of specific payout
class(es) that can be associated for the purpose of
specifying a financial product. For example, two
interest rate payouts can be combined to specify an
interest rate swap, or one interest rate payout can
be combined with a credit default payout to specify a
credit default swap.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>Payout</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>
<th align="left">Type/Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>cashflow</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>Cashflow</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A cashflow between the parties to the trade. For interest rate and equity products, this corresponds to the FpML additionalPayment element. For credit default swaps, this corresponds to the FpML initialPayment element and the singlePayment element of the fee leg. For option products, it represents the FpML premium element.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>creditDefaultPayout</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>CreditDefaultPayout</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The credit default payout, which provides the details necessary for determining when a credit payout will be triggered as well as the parameters for calculating the payout and the settlement terms.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>equityPayout</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>EquityPayout</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The equity payout, which encompasses the equity price returns, dividend returns, volatility and variance return provisions.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>forwardPayout</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>ForwardPayout</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>interestRatePayout</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>InterestRatePayout</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">All of the terms necessary to define and calculate a cash flow based on a fixed, a floating or an inflation index rate. The interest rate payout can be applied to interest rate swaps and FRA (which both have two associated interest rate payouts), credit default swaps (to represent the fee leg when subject to periodic payments) and equity swaps (to represent the funding leg).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>optionPayout</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>OptionPayout</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The option payout.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</li>
</ul>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-physicalsettlementterms" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-physicalsettlementterms"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>PhysicalSettlementTerms</code></h3>
<p>In FpML, PhysicalSettlementTerms and
CashSettlementTerms extend SettlementTerms.  In the
CDM, this extension paradigm has not been used
because SettlementTerms class has been used for
purposes related to securities transactions, while it
is not used as such in the FpML standard (i.e. only
as an abstract construct.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>PhysicalSettlementTerms</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>

<td align="left">If this element is specified and set to 'true', indicates that physical settlement must take place through the use of an escrow agent. (For Canadian counterparties this is always 'Not Applicable'. ISDA 2003 Term: Escrow.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>id</code></td>
