<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The number of business days used in the determination of the physical settlement date. The physical settlement date is this number of business days after all applicable conditions to settlement are satisfied. If a number of business days is not specified fallback provisions apply for determining the number of business days. If Section 8.5/8.6 of the 1999/2003 ISDA Definitions are to apply the businessDaysNotSpecified element should be included. If a specified number of business days are to apply these should be specified in the businessDays element. If Section 8.5/8.6 of the 1999/2003 ISDA Definitions are to apply but capped at a maximum number of business days then the maximum number should be specified in the maximumBusinessDays element. ISDA 2003 Term: Physical Settlement Period.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>settlementCurrency</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>(</code> <code>FieldWithMeta</code> <code>Text</code> <code>)</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The settlement currency is to be specified when the Settlement Amount cannot be known in advance. The list of valid currencies is not presently positioned as an enumeration as part of the CDM because that scope is limited to the values specified by ISDA and FpML. As a result, implementers have to make reference to the relevant standard, such as the ISO 4217 standard for currency codes.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>sixtyBusinessDaySettlementCap</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">If this element is specified and set to 'true', for a transaction documented under the 2003 ISDA Credit Derivatives Definitions, has the effect of incorporating the language set forth below into the confirmation. The section references are to the 2003 ISDA Credit Derivatives Definitions. Notwithstanding Section 1.7 or any provisions of Sections 9.9 or 9.10 to the contrary, but without prejudice to Section 9.3 and (where applicable) Sections 9.4, 9.5 and 9.6, if the Termination Date has not occurred on or prior to the date that is 60 Business Days following the Physical Settlement Date, such 60th Business Day shall be deemed to be the Termination Date with respect to this Transaction except in relation to any portion of the Transaction (an 'Affected Portion') in respect of which: (1) a valid notice of Buy-in Price has been delivered that is effective fewer than three Business Days prior to such 60th Business Day, in which case the Termination Date for that Affected Portion shall be the third Business Day following the date on which such notice is effective; or (2) Buyer has purchased but not Delivered Deliverable Obligations validly specified by Seller pursuant to Section 9.10(b), in which case the Termination Date for that Affected Portion shall be the tenth Business Day following the date on which Seller validly specified such Deliverable Obligations to Buyer.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</li>
</ul>

<p>A class to combine the CDM product qualifier with
other product qualifiers, such as the FpML ones.
While the CDM product qualifier is derived by the CDM
from the product payout features, the other product
identification elements are assigned by some external
sources and correspond to values specified by other
data representation protocols.</p>
<ul>
<li>

<th align="left">Field</th>

</thead>

<tr>

</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A classification of the most important risk class of the trade. FpML defines a simple asset class categorisation using a coding scheme.</td>

<tr>
<td align="left"><code>productId</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>FieldWithMeta</code> <code>Text</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A product reference identifier. The product Id is an identifier that describes the key economic characteristics of the trade type, with the exception of concepts such as size (notional, quantity, number of units) and price (fixed rate, strike, etc.) that are negotiated for each transaction. It can be used to hold identifiers such as the 'UPI' (universal product identifier) required by certain regulatory reporting rules. It can also be used to hold identifiers of benchmark products or product temnplates used by certain trading systems or facilities. FpML does not define the domain values associated with this element. Note that the domain values for this element are not strictly an enumerated list.</td>
</tr>

<tr>

</tr>
<tr>

</tr>

</table>
</li>
</ul>

</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>id</code></td>

</tr>
<tr>

</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>observedRate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Decimal</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The actual observed rate before any required rate treatment is applied, e.g. before converting a rate quoted on a discount basis to an equivalent yield. An observed rate of 5% would be represented as 0.05.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>rateReference</code></td>

<tr>
<td align="left"><code>treatedForecastRate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Decimal</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>

</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>treatedRate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Decimal</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>

</tr>

</table>

<ul>

<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>

</thead>
<tbody>

</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Indicates whether an obligation of the Reference Entity, guaranteed by the Reference Entity on behalf of a non-Affiliate, is to be considered an Obligation for the purpose of the transaction. It will be considered an obligation if allGuarantees is applicable (true) and not if allGuarantees is inapplicable (false). ISDA 2003 Term: All Guarantees.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>noReferenceObligation</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Used to indicate that there is no Reference Obligation associated with this Credit Default Swap and that there will never be one.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>referenceEntity</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>LegalEntity</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The corporate or sovereign entity which is subject to the swap transaction and any successor that assumes all or substantially all of its contractual and other obligations. Reference Entities cannot be senior or subordinated. It is the obligations of the Reference Entities that can be senior or subordinated. ISDA 2014 Credit definitions article II section 2.1: <code>Reference Entity</code> means the entity specified as such in the related Confirmation.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>referenceObligation</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>ReferenceObligation</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The Reference Obligation is a financial instrument that is either issued or guaranteed by the reference entity. It serves to clarify the precise reference entity protection is being offered upon, and its legal position with regard to other related firms (parents/subsidiaries). Furthermore the Reference Obligation is ALWAYS deliverable and establishes the Pari Passu ranking (as the deliverable bonds must rank equal to the reference obligation). ISDA 2003 Term: Reference Obligation.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>referencePolicy</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Applicable to the transactions on mortgage-backed security, which can make use of a reference policy. Presence of the element with value set to 'true' indicates that the reference policy is applicable; absence implies that it is not.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>referencePrice</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Decimal</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Used to determine (a) for physically settled trades, the Physical Settlement Amount, which equals the Floating Rate Payer Calculation Amount times the Reference Price and (b) for cash settled trades, the Cash Settlement Amount, which equals the greater of (i) the difference between the Reference Price and the Final Price and (ii) zero. ISDA 2003 Term: Reference Price.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>securedList</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">With respect to any day, the list of Syndicated Secured Obligations of the Designated Priority of the Reference Entity published by Markit Group Limited or any successor thereto appointed by the Specified Dealers (the 'Secured List Publisher') on or most recently before such day, which list is currently available at [<a href="http://www.markit.com" rel="nofollow">http://www.markit.com</a>]. ISDA 2003 Term: Relevant Secured List.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>unknownReferenceObligation</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Bool</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Used to indicate that the Reference obligation associated with the Credit Default Swap is currently not known. This is not valid for Legal Confirmation purposes, but is valid for earlier stages in the trade life cycle (e.g. Broker Confirmation).</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td align="left"><code>referenceEntity</code></td>

</tr>
<tr>

Please note, Reference Entities cannot be senior or subordinated. It is the obligations of the Reference Entities that can be senior or subordinated. ISDA 2003 Term: Reference Entity.</td>
</tr>
<tr>

ISDA 2003 Term: Reference Obligation.</td>

</li>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-relativedateoffset" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-relativedateoffset"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>RelativeDateOffset</code></h3>
<p>A class defining a date (referred to as the derived
date) as a relative offset from another date
(referred to as the anchor date). If the anchor date
is itself an adjustable date then the offset is
assumed to be calculated from the adjusted anchor
date. A number of different scenarios can be
supported, namely; 1) the derived date may simply be
a number of calendar periods (days, weeks, months or
years) preceding or following the anchor date; 2) the
unadjusted derived date may be a number of calendar
periods (days, weeks, months or years) preceding or
following the anchor date with the resulting
unadjusted derived date subject to adjustment in
accordance with a specified business day convention,
i.e. the derived date must fall on a good business
day; 3) the derived date may be a number of business
days preceding or following the anchor date. Note
that the businessDayConvention specifies any required
adjustment to the unadjusted derived date. A negative
or positive value in the periodMultiplier indicates
whether the unadjusted derived precedes or follows
the anchor date. The businessDayConvention should
contain a value NONE if the day type element contains
a value of Business (since specifying a negative or
positive business days offset would already guarantee
that the derived date would fall on a good business
day in the specified business centers).</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>RelativeDateOffset</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>
<th align="left">Type/Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>adjustedDate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Date</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The date once the adjustment has been performed. (Note that this date may change if the business center holidays change).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>businessCenters</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>BusinessCenters</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>businessCentersReference</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>(</code> <code>ReferenceWithMeta</code> <code>BusinessCenters</code> <code>)</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A pointer style reference to a set of financial business centers defined elsewhere in the document. This set of business centers is used to determine whether a particular day is a business day or not.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>businessDayConvention</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>BusinessDayConventionEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The convention for adjusting a date if it would otherwise fall on a day that is not a business day, as specified by an ISDA convention (e.g. Following, Precedent).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>dateRelativeTo</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>(</code> <code>BasicReferenceWithMeta</code> <code>Date</code> <code>)</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Specifies the anchor as an href attribute. The href attribute value is a pointer style reference to the element or component elsewhere in the document where the anchor date is defined.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>dayType</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>DayTypeEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">In the case of an offset specified as a number of days, this element defines whether consideration is given as to whether a day is a good business day or not. If a day type of business days is specified then non-business days are ignored when calculating the offset. The financial business centers to use for determination of business days are implied by the context in which this element is used. This element must only be included when the offset is specified as a number of days. If the offset is zero days then the dayType element should not be included.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>id</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>period</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>PeriodEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A time period, e.g. a day, week, month or year of the stream. If the periodMultiplier value is 0 (zero) then period must contain the value D (day).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>periodMultiplier</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Int</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A time period multiplier, e.g. 1, 2 or 3 etc. A negative value can be used when specifying an offset relative to another date, e.g. -2 days.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</li>
</ul>
<h3><a id="user-content-data-relativedates" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-relativedates"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>RelativeDates</code></h3>
<p>A class describing a set of dates defined as relative
to another set of dates.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>RelativeDates</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>
<th align="left">Type/Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>adjustedDate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Date</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The date once the adjustment has been performed. (Note that this date may change if the business center holidays change).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>businessCenters</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>BusinessCenters</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>businessCentersReference</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>(</code> <code>ReferenceWithMeta</code> <code>BusinessCenters</code> <code>)</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A pointer style reference to a set of financial business centers defined elsewhere in the document. This set of business centers is used to determine whether a particular day is a business day or not.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>businessDayConvention</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>BusinessDayConventionEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The convention for adjusting a date if it would otherwise fall on a day that is not a business day, as specified by an ISDA convention (e.g. Following, Precedent).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>dateRelativeTo</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>(</code> <code>BasicReferenceWithMeta</code> <code>Date</code> <code>)</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Specifies the anchor as an href attribute. The href attribute value is a pointer style reference to the element or component elsewhere in the document where the anchor date is defined.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>dayType</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>DayTypeEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">In the case of an offset specified as a number of days, this element defines whether consideration is given as to whether a day is a good business day or not. If a day type of business days is specified then non-business days are ignored when calculating the offset. The financial business centers to use for determination of business days are implied by the context in which this element is used. This element must only be included when the offset is specified as a number of days. If the offset is zero days then the dayType element should not be included.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>id</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>period</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>PeriodEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A time period, e.g. a day, week, month or year of the stream. If the periodMultiplier value is 0 (zero) then period must contain the value D (day).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>periodMultiplier</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Int</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A time period multiplier, e.g. 1, 2 or 3 etc. A negative value can be used when specifying an offset relative to another date, e.g. -2 days.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>periodSkip</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Int</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The number of periods in the referenced date schedule that are between each date in the relative date schedule. Thus a skip of 2 would mean that dates are relative to every second date in the referenced schedule. If present this should have a value greater than 1.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>scheduleBounds</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>DateRange</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The first and last dates of a schedule. This can be used to restrict the range of values in a reference series of dates.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</li>
</ul>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-resetdates" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-resetdates"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>ResetDates</code></h3>
<p>A class defining the parameters used to generate the
reset dates schedule and associated fixing dates. The
reset dates are the dates on which the new index
value (which is observed on the fixing date) is
applied for each period and on which the interest
rate hence begins to accrue.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>ResetDates</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>
<th align="left">Type/Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>calculationPeriodDatesReference</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>(</code> <code>ReferenceWithMeta</code> <code>CalculationPeriodDates</code> <code>)</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A pointer style reference to the associated calculation period dates component defined elsewhere in the document.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>finalFixingDate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>AdjustableDate</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">This attribute is not part of the FpML ResetDate, and has been added as part of the CDM to support the credit derivatives final fixing date.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>fixingDates</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>RelativeDateOffset</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The fixing dates are the dates on which the index values are observed. The fixing dates are specified by reference to the reset date through business days offset and an associated set of financial business centers. Normally these offset calculation rules will be those specified in the ISDA definition for the relevant floating rate index (ISDA's Floating Rate Option). However, non-standard offset calculation rules may apply for a trade if mutually agreed by the principal parties to the transaction.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>id</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>initialFixingDate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>InitialFixingDate</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The initial fixing date.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>rateCutOffDaysOffset</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Offset</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Specifies the number of business days before the period end date when the rate cut-off date is assumed to apply. The financial business centers associated with determining the rate cut-off date are those specified in the reset dates adjustments. The rate cut-off number of days must be a negative integer (a value of zero would imply no rate cut off applies in which case the rateCutOffDaysOffset element should not be included). The relevant rate for each reset date in the period from, and including, a rate cut-off date to, but excluding, the next applicable period end date (or, in the case of the last calculation period, the termination date) will (solely for purposes of calculating the floating amount payable on the next applicable payment date) be deemed to be the relevant rate in effect on that rate cut-off date. For example, if rate cut-off days for a daily averaging deal is -2 business days, then the refix rate applied on (period end date - 2 days) will also be applied as the reset on (period end date - 1 day), i.e. the actual number of reset dates remains the same but from the rate cut-off date until the period end date, the same refix rate is applied. Note that in the case of several calculation periods contributing to a single payment, the rate cut-off is assumed only to apply to the final calculation period contributing to that payment. The day type associated with the offset must imply a business days offset.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>resetDatesAdjustments</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>BusinessDayAdjustments</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The definition of the business day convention and financial business centers used for adjusting the reset date if it would otherwise fall on a day that is not a business day in the specified business center.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>resetFrequency</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>ResetFrequency</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The frequency at which the reset dates occur. In the case of a weekly reset frequency, also specifies the day of the week that the reset occurs. If the reset frequency is greater than the calculation period frequency then this implies that more than one reset is established for each calculation period and some form of rate averaging is applicable.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>resetRelativeTo</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>ResetRelativeToEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Specifies whether the reset dates are determined with respect to each adjusted calculation period start date or adjusted calculation period end date.  If the reset frequency is specified as daily this element must not be included.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</li>
</ul>
<h3><a id="user-content-data-resetfrequency" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-resetfrequency"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>ResetFrequency</code></h3>
<p>A class defining the reset frequency. In the case of
a weekly reset, also specifies the day of the week
that the reset occurs. If the reset frequency is
greater than the calculation period frequency the
this implies that more or more reset dates is
established for each calculation period and some form
of rate averaging is applicable. The specific
averaging method of calculation is specified in
FloatingRateCalculation. In case the reset frequency
is of value T (term), the period is defined by the
swap/swapStream/calculationPerioDates/effectiveDate
and the
swap/swapStream/calculationPerioDates/terminationDate.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>ResetFrequency</code></p>
<table>

</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>period</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>PeriodExtendedEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A time period, e.g. a day, week, month, year or term of the stream.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>periodMultiplier</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Int</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A time period multiplier, e.g. 1, 2, or 3. If the period value is T (Term) then period multiplier must contain the value 1.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>weeklyRollConvention</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>WeeklyRollConventionEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The day of the week on which a weekly reset date occurs. This element must be included if the reset frequency is defined as weekly and not otherwise.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-resource" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-resource"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>Resource</code></h3>
<p>Describes the resource that contains the media
representation of a business event (i.e used for
stating the Publicly Available Information). For
example, can describe a file or a URL that represents
the event. This type is an extended version of a type
defined by RIXML (<a href="http://www.rixml.org" rel="nofollow">www.rixml.org</a>).  Rosetta restricts
the FpML implementation by not providing the ability
to associated a document in hexadecimalBinary or
base64Binary until such time that actual use cases
will come up.</p>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-resourcelength" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-resourcelength"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>ResourceLength</code></h3>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-stubcalculationperiodamount" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-stubcalculationperiodamount"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>StubCalculationPeriodAmount</code></h3>
<p>A class defining how the initial or final stub
calculation period amounts is calculated. For
example, the rate to be applied to the initial or
final stub calculation period may be the linear
interpolation of two different tenors for the
floating rate index specified in the calculation
period amount component, e.g. A two month stub period
may used the linear interpolation of a one month and
three month floating rate. The different rate tenors
would be specified in this component. Note that a
maximum of two rate tenors can be specified. If a
stub period uses a single index tenor and this is the
same as that specified in the calculation period
amount component then the initial stub or final stub
component, as the case may be, must not be included.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>StubCalculationPeriodAmount</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>
<th align="left">Type/Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>calculationPeriodDatesReference</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>ReferenceWithMeta</code> <code>CalculationPeriodDates</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A pointer style reference to the associated calculation period dates component defined elsewhere in the document.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>finalStub</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>StubValue</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Specifies how the final stub amount is calculated. A single floating rate tenor different to that used for the regular part of the calculation periods schedule may be specified, or two floating tenors may be specified. If two floating rate tenors are specified then Linear Interpolation (in accordance with the 2000 ISDA Definitions, Section 8.3. Interpolation) is assumed to apply. Alternatively, an actual known stub rate or stub amount may be specified.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>initialStub</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>StubValue</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Specifies how the initial stub amount is calculated. A single floating rate tenor different to that used for the regular part of the calculation periods schedule may be specified, or two floating tenors may be specified. If two floating rate tenors are specified then Linear Interpolation (in accordance with the 2000 ISDA Definitions, Section 8.3. Interpolation) is assumed to apply. Alternatively, an actual known stub rate or stub amount may be specified.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</li>
</ul>
<h3><a id="user-content-data-stubfloatingrate" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-stubfloatingrate"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>StubFloatingRate</code></h3>
<p>A class defining a floating rate.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>StubFloatingRate</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>
<th align="left">Type/Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>capRateSchedule</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>StrikeSchedule</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The cap rate or cap rate schedule, if any, which applies to the floating rate. The cap rate (strike) is only required where the floating rate on a swap stream is capped at a certain level. A cap rate schedule is expressed as explicit cap rates and dates and the step dates may be subject to adjustment in accordance with any adjustments specified in calculationPeriodDatesAdjustments. The cap rate is assumed to be exclusive of any spread and is a per annum rate, expressed as a decimal. A cap rate of 5% would be represented as 0.05.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>floatingRateIndex</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>FloatingRateIndexEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The floating rate index.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>floatingRateMultiplierSchedule</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Schedule</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A rate multiplier or multiplier schedule to apply to the floating rate. A multiplier schedule is expressed as explicit multipliers and dates. In the case of a schedule, the step dates may be subject to adjustment in accordance with any adjustments specified in the calculationPeriodDatesAdjustments. The multiplier can be a positive or negative decimal. This element should only be included if the multiplier is not equal to 1 (one) for the term of the stream.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>floorRateSchedule</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>StrikeSchedule</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The floor rate or floor rate schedule, if any, which applies to the floating rate. The floor rate (strike) is only required where the floating rate on a swap stream is floored at a certain strike level. A floor rate schedule is expressed as explicit floor rates and dates and the step dates may be subject to adjustment in accordance with any adjustments specified in calculationPeriodDatesAdjustments. The floor rate is assumed to be exclusive of any spread and is a per annum rate, expressed as a decimal. A floor rate of 5% would be represented as 0.05.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>id</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Text</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>indexTenor</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Period</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The ISDA Designated Maturity, i.e. the tenor of the floating rate.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>rateTreatment</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>RateTreatmentEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The specification of any rate conversion which needs to be applied to the observed rate before being used in any calculations. The two common conversions are for securities quoted on a bank discount basis which will need to be converted to either a Money Market Yield or Bond Equivalent Yield. See the Annex to the 2000 ISDA Definitions, Section 7.3. Certain General Definitions Relating to Floating Rate Options, paragraphs (g) and (h) for definitions of these terms.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>spreadSchedule</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>SpreadSchedule</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The ISDA Spread or a Spread schedule expressed as explicit spreads and dates. In the case of a schedule, the step dates may be subject to adjustment in accordance with any adjustments specified in calculationPeriodDatesAdjustments. The spread is a per annum rate, expressed as a decimal. For purposes of determining a calculation period amount, if positive the spread will be added to the floating rate and if negative the spread will be subtracted from the floating rate. A positive 10 basis point (0.1%) spread would be represented as 0.001.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-stubperiod" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-stubperiod"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>StubPeriod</code></h3>
<p>A class defining how the initial or final stub
calculation period amounts is calculated. For
example, the rate to be applied to the initial or
final stub calculation period may be the linear
interpolation of two different tenors for the
floating rate index specified in the calculation
period amount component, e.g. A two month stub period
may used the linear interpolation of a one month and
three month floating rate. The different rate tenors
would be specified in this component. Note that a
maximum of two rate tenors can be specified. If a
stub period uses a single index tenor and this is the
same as that specified in the calculation period
amount component then the initial stub or final stub
component, as the case may be, must not be included.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>StubPeriod</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>
<th align="left">Type/Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>calculationPeriodDatesReference</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>ReferenceWithMeta</code> <code>CalculationPeriodDates</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">A pointer style reference to the associated calculation period dates component defined elsewhere in the document.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>finalStub</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>StubValue</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Specifies how the final stub amount is calculated. A single floating rate tenor different to that used for the regular part of the calculation periods schedule may be specified, or two floating tenors may be specified. If two floating rate tenors are specified then Linear Interpolation (in accordance with the 2000 ISDA Definitions, Section 8.3. Interpolation) is assumed to apply. Alternatively, an actual known stub rate or stub amount may be specified.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>initialStub</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>StubValue</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">Specifies how the initial stub amount is calculated. A single floating rate tenor different to that used for the regular part of the calculation periods schedule may be specified, or two floating tenors may be specified. If two floating rate tenors are specified then Linear Interpolation (in accordance with the 2000 ISDA Definitions, Section 8.3. Interpolation) is assumed to apply. Alternatively, an actual known stub rate or stub amount may be specified.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</li>
</ul>
<h3><a id="user-content-data-stubvalue" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-stubvalue"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>StubValue</code></h3>
<p>A type defining how a stub calculation period amount
is calculated. A single floating rate tenor different
to that used for the regular part of the calculation
periods schedule may be specified, or two floating
rate tenors many be specified. If two floating rate
tenors are specified then Linear Interpolation (in
accordance with the 2000 ISDA Definitions, Section
8.3 Interpolation) is assumed to apply.
Alternatively, an actual known stub rate or stub
amount may be specified.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>StubValue</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>
<th align="left">Type/Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>floatingRate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>[</code> <code>StubFloatingRate</code> <code>]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">The rates to be applied to the initial or final stub may be the linear interpolation of two different rates. While the majority of the time, the rate indices will be the same as that specified in the stream and only the tenor itself will be different, it is possible to specift two different rates. For example, a 2 month stub period may use the linear interpolation of a 1 month and 3 month rate. The different rates would be specified in this component. Note that a maximum of two rates can be specified. If a stub period uses the same floating rate index, including tenor, as the regular calculation periods then this should not be specified again within this component, i.e. the stub calculation period amount component may not need to be specified even if there is an initial or final stub period. If a stub period uses a different floating rate index compared to the regular calculation periods then this should be specified within this component. If specified here, they are likely to have id attributes, allowing them to be referenced from within the cashflows component.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>stubAmount</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Money</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An actual amount to apply for the initial or final stub period may have been agreed between the two parties. If an actual stub amount has been agreed then it would be included in this component.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>stubRate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Decimal</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An actual rate to apply for the initial or final stub period may have been agreed between the principal parties (in a similar way to how an initial rate may have been agreed for the first regular period). If an actual stub rate has been agreed then it would be included in this component. It will be a per annum rate, expressed as a decimal. A stub rate of 5% would be represented as 0.05.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</li>
</ul>

can either be an execution or a contract. The
execution consists essentially in the economic terms
which are agreed between the parties. The contract
will further qualify those with the legal entities

can involve the investment adviser rather not the
actual funds) while not specify the master agreement
or collateral terms which might be associated with
the subsequent contract.</p>

<p>A class to represent the transacted price attributes
that are positioned as part of the FpML FeeLeg.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>TransactedPrice</code></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left">Field</th>
<th align="left">Type/Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>initialPoints</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Decimal</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An optional element that contains the up-front points expressed as a percentage of the notional. An initialPoints value of 5% would be represented as 0.05. The initialPoints element is an alternative to marketFixedRate in quoting the traded level of a trade. When initialPoints is used, the traded level is the sum of fixedRate and initialPoints. The initialPoints is one of the items that are factored into the initialPayment calculation and is payable by the Buyer to the Seller. Note that initialPoints and marketFixedRate may both be present in the same document when both implied values are desired.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>marketFixedRate</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Decimal</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An optional element that only has meaning in a credit index trade. This element contains the credit spread ('fair value') at which the trade was executed. Unlike the fixedRate of an index, the marketFixedRate varies over the life of the index depending on market conditions. The marketFixedRate is the price of the index as quoted by trading desks.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>marketPrice</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>Decimal</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An optional element that only has meaning in a credit index trade. This element contains the price at which the trade was executed and is used instead of marketFixedRate on credit trades on certain indicies which are quoted using a price rather than a spread.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"><code>quotationStyle</code></td>
<td align="left"><code>Optional</code> <code>QuotationStyleEnum</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left"></td>
<td align="left">An optional element that contains the up-front points expressed as a percentage of the notional. An initialPoints value of 5% would be represented as 0.05. The initialPoints element is an alternative to marketFixedRate in quoting the traded level of a trade. When initialPoints is used, the traded level is the sum of fixedRate and initialPoints. The initialPoints is one of the items that are factored into the initialPayment calculation and is payable by the Buyer to the Seller. Note that initialPoints and marketFixedRate may both be present in the same document when both implied values are desired.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</li>
</ul>

parties, those assets being either cash, securities
or physical assets. This class combines components
that are cross-assets (settlement date, settlement
type, status, ...) and some other which are
specialized by asset class (e.g. the payer/receiver
amount and cashflow type for a cash transfer, the
transferor/transferee, security indication, quantity,
and asset transfer type qualification for the case of
a security). The associated rosettaKey denotes the
ability to associate a hash value to the respective
Execution instantiations for the purpose of model
cross-referencing, in support of functionality such
as the event effect and the lineage.</p>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-accounttypeenum" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-accounttypeenum"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>AccountTypeEnum</code></h3>
<p>The enumeration values to qualify the type of
account.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>AccountTypeEnum_AggregateClient</code>
Aggregate client account, as defined under ESMA
MiFIR.</li>
<li><code>AccountTypeEnum_Client</code>
The account contains trading activity or positions
that belong to a client of the firm that opened the
account.</li>
<li><code>AccountTypeEnum_House</code>
The account contains proprietary trading activity or
positions, belonging to the firm that is the owner of
the account.</li>
</ul>
<h3><a id="user-content-data-actionenum" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-actionenum"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>ActionEnum</code></h3>
<p>The enumeration values to specify the actions
associated with transactions.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>ActionEnum_Cancel</code>
A cancellation of a prior instance of the transaction
event. The eventIdentifier has an associated version
greater than 1.</li>
<li><code>ActionEnum_Correct</code>
A correction of a prior instance of the transaction
event. The eventIdentifier has an associated version
greater than 1.</li>
<li><code>ActionEnum_New</code>
A new instance of a transaction event, which is also
characterized by the fact that the eventIdentifier
has an associated version 1.</li>
</ul>
<h3><a id="user-content-data-additionaltypeenum" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-additionaltypeenum"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>AdditionalTypeEnum</code></h3>
<p>The enumerated values to specify the Additional Type
of transaction that can require the collection or
delivery of initial margin under a given regulatory
regime for the purposes of Covered Transactions, as
specified in ISDA 2016 Credit Support Annex for
Initial Margin, paragraph 13, General Principles,
(b)(B).</p>
<ul>
<li><code>AdditionalTypeEnum_EquityOptionOrIndexOption</code>
Single stock equity option or index option
transaction as referred to in the transitional
provisions (if any) of the EMIR RTS.</li>
<li><code>AdditionalTypeEnum_NotApplicable</code>
No Additional Type of transaction is applicable to
the regulatory regulatory regime.</li>
<li><code>AdditionalTypeEnum_Other</code></li>
</ul>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-averaginginoutenum" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-averaginginoutenum"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>AveragingInOutEnum</code></h3>
<p>The enumerated values to specify the type of
averaging used in an Asian option.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>AveragingInOutEnum_Both</code>
The average price is used to derive both the strike
and the expiration price.</li>
<li><code>AveragingInOutEnum_In</code>
The average price is used to derive the strike price.
Also known as 'Asian strike' style option.</li>
<li><code>AveragingInOutEnum_Out</code>
The average price is used to derive the expiration
price. Also known as 'Asian price' style
option.</li>
</ul>
<h3><a id="user-content-data-averagingmethodenum" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-averagingmethodenum"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>AveragingMethodEnum</code></h3>
<p>The enumerated values to specify the method of
calculation to be used when averaging rates. Per ISDA
2000 Definitions, Section 6.2. Certain Definitions
Relating to Floating Amounts.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>AveragingMethodEnum_Unweighted</code>
The arithmetic mean of the relevant rates for each
reset date.</li>
<li><code>AveragingMethodEnum_Weighted</code>
The arithmetic mean of the relevant rates in effect
for each day in a calculation period calculated by
multiplying each relevant rate by the number of days
such relevant rate is in effect, determining the sum
of such products and dividing such sum by the number
of days in the calculation period.</li>
</ul>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-businessdayconventionenum" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-businessdayconventionenum"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>BusinessDayConventionEnum</code></h3>
<p>The enumerated values to specify the convention for
adjusting any relevant date if it would otherwise
fall on a day that is not a valid business day.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>BusinessDayConventionEnum_FOLLOWING</code>
The non-business date will be adjusted to the first
following day that is a business day</li>
<li><code>BusinessDayConventionEnum_FRN</code>
Per 2000 ISDA Definitions, Section 4.11. FRN
Convention; Eurodollar Convention. FRN is included
here as a type of business day convention although it
does not strictly fall within ISDA's definition
of a Business Day Convention and does not conform to
the simple definition given above.</li>
<li><code>BusinessDayConventionEnum_MODFOLLOWING</code>
The non-business date will be adjusted to the first
following day that is a business day unless that day
falls in the next calendar month, in which case that
date will be the first preceding day that is a
business day.</li>
<li><code>BusinessDayConventionEnum_MODPRECEDING</code>
The non-business date will be adjusted to the first
preceding day that is a business day unless that day
falls in the previous calendar month, in which case
that date will be the first following day that us a
business day.</li>
<li><code>BusinessDayConventionEnum_NEAREST</code>
The non-business date will be adjusted to the nearest
day that is a business day - i.e. if the non-business
day falls on any day other than a Sunday or a Monday,
it will be the first preceding day that is a business
day, and will be the first following business day if
it falls on a Sunday or a Monday.</li>
<li><code>BusinessDayConventionEnum_NONE</code>
The date will not be adjusted if it falls on a day
that is not a business day.</li>
<li><code>BusinessDayConventionEnum_NotApplicable</code>
The date adjustments conventions are defined
elsewhere, so it is not required to specify them
here.</li>
<li><code>BusinessDayConventionEnum_PRECEDING</code>
The non-business day will be adjusted to the first
preceding day that is a business day.</li>
</ul>
<h3><a id="user-content-data-calculationagentpartyenum" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-calculationagentpartyenum"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>CalculationAgentPartyEnum</code></h3>
<p>The enumerated values to specify how a calculation
agent will be determined.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>CalculationAgentPartyEnum_AsSpecifiedInMasterAgreement</code>
The Calculation Agent is determined by reference to
the relevant master agreement.</li>
<li><code>CalculationAgentPartyEnum_AsSpecifiedInStandardTermsSupplement</code>
The Calculation Agent is determined by reference to
the relevant standard terms supplement.</li>
<li><code>CalculationAgentPartyEnum_Both</code>
Both parties with joined rights to be a calculation
agent.</li>
<li><code>CalculationAgentPartyEnum_ExercisingParty</code>
The party that gives notice of exercise. Per 2000
ISDA Definitions, Section 11.1. Parties, paragraph
(d).</li>
<li><code>CalculationAgentPartyEnum_NonExercisingParty</code>
The party that is given notice of exercise. Per 2000
ISDA Definitions, Section 11.1. Parties, paragraph
(e).</li>
</ul>
<h3><a id="user-content-data-cashflowtypeenum" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-cashflowtypeenum"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>CashflowTypeEnum</code></h3>
<p>The qualification of the type of cash flows
associated with OTC derivatives contracts and their
lifecycle events.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_AmendmentFee</code>
A cash flow associated with an amendment lifecycle
event.</li>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_AssignmentFee</code>
A cash flow resulting from the assignment of a
contract to a new counterparty.</li>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_BrokerageCommission</code>
The brokerage commission.</li>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_Coupon</code>
A cash flow corresponding to the periodic accrued
interests.</li>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_CreditEvent</code>
A cashflow resulting from a credit event.</li>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_DividendReturn</code>
A cash flow corresponding to the synthetic dividend
of an equity underlier asset traded through a
derivative instrument.</li>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_ExerciseFee</code>
A cash flow associated with an exercise lifecycle
event.</li>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_Fee</code>
A generic term for describing a non-scheduled
cashflow that can be associated either with the
initial contract, with some later corrections to it
(e.g. a correction to the day count fraction that has
a cashflow impact) or with some lifecycle events.
Fees that are specifically associated with
termination and partial termination, increase,
amendment, and exercise events are qualified
accordingly.</li>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_IncreaseFee</code>
A cash flow associated with an increase lifecycle
event.</li>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_Interest</code>
Interest, without qualification as to whether it a
gross or net interest relates cashflow.</li>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_InterestReturn</code>
A cash flow corresponding to the return of the
interest rate portion of a derivative instrument that
has different types of underlying assets, such as a
total return swap.</li>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_NetInterest</code>
Net interest across payout components. Applicable to
products such as interest rate swaps.</li>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_NovationFee</code>
The novation fee.</li>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_PartialTerminationFee</code>
A cash flow associated with a partial termination
lifecycle event.</li>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_Premium</code>
The premium associated with an OTC contract such as
an option or a cap/floor.</li>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_PriceReturn</code>
A cash flow corresponding to the return of the price
portion of a derivative instrument that has different
types of underlying assets, such as a total return
swap.</li>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_PrincipalExchange</code>
A cash flow which amount typically corresponds to the
notional of the contract and that is exchanged
between the parties on trade inception and reverted
back when the contract is terminated.</li>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_TerminationFee</code>
A cash flow associated with a termination lifecycle
event.</li>
<li><code>CashflowTypeEnum_UpfrontFee</code>
An upfront cashflow associated to the swap to adjust
for a difference between the swap price and the
current market price.</li>
</ul>
<h3><a id="user-content-data-categoryenum" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-categoryenum"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>CategoryEnum</code></h3>
<p>The enumerated values to specify the type of
organisation involved in the transaction.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>CategoryEnum_Agent</code>
The trade or trade report represents the information
from the perspective of the sender of the report,
typically a clearing member firm or dealer (acting as
an agent).</li>
<li><code>CategoryEnum_Counterparty</code>
The trade or trade report represents the information
from the perspective of the counterparty of the
sender of the report, which is typically a clearing
member firm or dealer.</li>
<li><code>CategoryEnum_Customer</code>
The trade or trade report represents the information
from the perspective of a client opposite the sender
of the report, which is typically a clearing member
firm or dealer.</li>
<li><code>CategoryEnum_Principal</code>
The trade or trade report represents the information
from the perspective of the sender of the report,
typically a clearing member firm or dealer (acting as
a principal).</li>
</ul>
<h3><a id="user-content-data-closedstateenum" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-closedstateenum"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>ClosedStateEnum</code></h3>
<p>The enumerated values to specify what led to the
contract or execution closure.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>ClosedStateEnum_Allocated</code>
The execution or contract has been allocated.</li>
<li><code>ClosedStateEnum_Cancelled</code>
The execution or contract has been cancelled.</li>
<li><code>ClosedStateEnum_Exercised</code>
The (option) contract has been exercised.</li>
<li><code>ClosedStateEnum_Expired</code>
The (option) contract has expired without being
exercised.</li>
<li><code>ClosedStateEnum_Matured</code>
The contract has reached its contractual termination
date.</li>
<li><code>ClosedStateEnum_Novated</code>
The contract has been novated. This state applies to
the stepped-out contract component of the novation
event.</li>
<li><code>ClosedStateEnum_Terminated</code>
The contract has been subject of an early termination
event.</li>
</ul>

<p>The enumerated values to specify the type of
compounding, e.g. flat, straight.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>CompoundingMethodEnum_Flat</code>
Flat compounding. Compounding excludes the spread.
Note that the first compounding period has it's
interest calculated including any spread then
subsequent periods compound this at a rate excluding
the spread.</li>
<li><code>CompoundingMethodEnum_None</code>
No compounding is to be applied.</li>
<li><code>CompoundingMethodEnum_SpreadExclusive</code>
Spread Exclusive compounding.</li>
<li><code>CompoundingMethodEnum_Straight</code>
Straight compounding. Compounding includes the
spread.</li>
</ul>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-daycountfractionenum" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-daycountfractionenum"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>DayCountFractionEnum</code></h3>
<p>The enumerated values to specify the day count
fraction.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>DayCountFractionEnum_ACT_360</code>
Per 2006 ISDA Definitions, Section 4.16. Day Count
Fraction, paragraph (e) or Annex to the 2000 ISDA
Definitions (June 2000 Version), Section 4.16. Day
Count Fraction, paragraph (d).</li>
<li><code>DayCountFractionEnum_ACT_365L</code>
Per 2006 ISDA Definitions, Section 4.16. Day Count
Fraction, paragraph (i).</li>
<li><code>DayCountFractionEnum_ACT_365_FIXED</code>
Per 2006 ISDA Definitions, Section 4.16. Day Count
Fraction, paragraph (d) or Annex to the 2000 ISDA
Definitions (June 2000 Version), Section 4.16. Day
Count Fraction, paragraph (c).</li>
<li><code>DayCountFractionEnum_ACT_ACT_AFB</code>
The Fixed/Floating Amount will be calculated in
accordance with the 'BASE EXACT/EXACT' day
count fraction, as defined in the 'Definitions
Communes plusieurs Additifs Techniques' published
by the Association Francaise des Banques in September
1994.</li>
<li><code>DayCountFractionEnum_ACT_ACT_ICMA</code>
Per 2006 ISDA Definitions, Section 4.16. Day Count
Fraction, paragraph (c). This day count fraction code
is applicable for transactions booked under the 2006
ISDA Definitions. Transactions under the 2000 ISDA
Definitions should use the ACT/ACT.ISMA code instead.</li>
<li><code>DayCountFractionEnum_ACT_ACT_ISDA</code>
Per 2006 ISDA Definitions, Section 4.16. Day Count
Fraction, paragraph (b) or Annex to the 2000 ISDA
Definitions (June 2000 Version), Section 4.16. Day
Count Fraction, paragraph (b). Note that going from
FpML 2.0 Recommendation to the FpML 3.0 Trial
Recommendation the code in FpML 2.0
'ACT/365.ISDA' became 'ACT/ACT.ISDA'.</li>
<li><code>DayCountFractionEnum_BUS_252</code>
The number of Business Days in the Calculation Period
or Compounding Period in respect of which payment is
being made divided by 252.</li>
<li><code>DayCountFractionEnum_RBA_BOND_BASIS_ANNUAL</code>
Per 2006 ISDA Definitions Supplement number 43, Day
Count Fraction, (k)if “RBA Bond Basis (semi-annual)”
is specified, 0.5. However, Actual/Actual (ISDA)
applies to each of the first Calculation Period and
the final Calculation Period if such Calculation
Period is less than six months</li>
<li><code>DayCountFractionEnum_RBA_BOND_BASIS_QUARTER</code>
Per 2006 ISDA Definitions Supplement number 43, Day
Count Fraction, if “RBA Bond Basis (quarter)” is
specified, 0.25. However, Actual/Actual (ISDA)
applies to each of the first Calculation Period and
the final Calculation Period if such Calculation
Period is less than three months</li>
<li><code>DayCountFractionEnum_RBA_BOND_BASIS_SEMI_ANNUAL</code>
Per 2006 ISDA Definitions Supplement number 43, Day
Count Fraction, if “RBA Bond Basis (semi-annual)” is
specified, 0.5. However, Actual/Actual (ISDA) applies
to each of the first Calculation Period and the final
Calculation Period if such Calculation Period is less
than six months</li>
<li><code>DayCountFractionEnum__1_1</code>
Per 2006 ISDA Definitions, Section 4.16. Day Count
Fraction, paragraph (a) or Annex to the 2000 ISDA
Definitions (June 2000 Version), Section 4.16. Day
Count Fraction, paragraph (a).</li>
<li><code>DayCountFractionEnum__30E_360</code>
Per 2006 ISDA Definitions, Section 4.16. Day Count
Fraction, paragraph (g) or Annex to the 2000 ISDA
Definitions (June 2000 Version), Section 4.16. Day
Count Fraction, paragraph (f). Note that the
algorithm defined for this day count fraction has
changed between the 2000 ISDA Definitions and 2006
ISDA Definitions. See Introduction to the 2006 ISDA
Definitions for further information relating to this
change.</li>
<li><code>DayCountFractionEnum__30E_360_ISDA</code>
Per 2006 ISDA Definitions, Section 4.16. Day Count
Fraction, paragraph (h). Note the algorithm for this
day count fraction under the 2006 ISDA Definitions is
designed to yield the same results in practice as the
version of the 30E/360 day count fraction defined in
the 2000 ISDA Definitions. See Introduction to the
2006 ISDA Definitions for further information
relating to this change.</li>
<li><code>DayCountFractionEnum__30_360</code>
Per 2006 ISDA Definitions, Section 4.16. Day Count
Fraction, paragraph (f) or Annex to the 2000 ISDA
Definitions (June 2000 Version), Section 4.16. Day
Count Fraction, paragraph (e).</li>
</ul>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-daytypeenum" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-daytypeenum"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>DayTypeEnum</code></h3>

classification used in counting the number of days
between two dates.</p>
<ul>

the count includes only business days.</li>
<li><code>DayTypeEnum_Calendar</code>
When calculating the number of days between two dates
the count includes all calendar days.</li>
<li><code>DayTypeEnum_CommodityBusiness</code>
When calculating the number of days between two dates
the count includes only commodity business days.</li>
<li><code>DayTypeEnum_CurrencyBusiness</code>
When calculating the number of days between two dates
the count includes only currency business days.</li>
<li><code>DayTypeEnum_ExchangeBusiness</code>
When calculating the number of days between two dates
the count includes only stock exchange business days.</li>
<li><code>DayTypeEnum_ScheduledTradingDay</code>
When calculating the number of days between two dates
the count includes only scheduled trading days.</li>
</ul>

<h3><a id="user-content-data-discountingtypeenum" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#data-discountingtypeenum"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><code>data</code> <code>DiscountingTypeEnum</code></h3>

<li><code>DiscountingTypeEnum_Standard</code>
